article.description: The Detroit Pistons don't expect their popularity to increase now that they have the best record in the Eastern Conference.
article.headline: Pistons speak out from atop Eastern Conference
article.linkText: Pistons beat Toronto then say nobody loves them
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- The Detroit Pistons don't expect their popularity to increase now that they have the best record in the Eastern Conference. "I don't think people want to see us win,'' Detroit's Chucky Atkins said after the Pistons defeated Toronto 89-84 Wednesday night. "Do I expect us to get any recognition? No. We don't have the type of guys that the NBA likes to market.'' Chauncey Billups scored 18 points, including a key 3-pointer with 19.4 seconds left, as the Pistons won for the ninth time in 10 games. Corliss Williamson added 16 points for the Pistons, who improved to 37-16 overall and 17-11 on the road. Only Dallas has a better road record. "They can all talk about Indiana and New Jersey and we'll continue to win ballgames,'' said Jon Barry, who had 10 of Detroit's 46 points off the bench. "I know we don't have the star appeal. Ben Wallace is probably the only player we have that people really know, but we got some great players here.'' Toronto went on a 11-2 run to cut Detroit's lead to two with 3:02 left, but Billups' jumper gave Detroit a four-point lead with 1:38 left. Toronto's Alvin Williams made a jumper from the top of the key to cut it two with 41 seconds left. After Toronto's defense collapsed on Williamson, he passed to a wide open Billups for a 3-pointer that gave Detroit a five-point lead with 19.4 seconds remaining. "When the defense collapsed, Chauncey was in the corner ... so I threw him the ball and let him do his thing,'' Williamson said. Toronto's Jerome Williams made a jumper to cut the lead to three before Richard Hamilton made two free throws to give Detroit a 89-84 lead with 14 seconds left. Hamilton, who averaged 28.5 points in his previous four games, went 1-for-9 from the field and finished with just four points. Detroit's bench outscored Toronto's 46-12. "Our bench gets the game ball tonight,'' Detroit coach Rick Carlisle said. "We were struggling and they really picked us up.'' Vince Carter scored 16 points -- only two in the second half -- in his first game since declaring that the Raptors can still make the playoffs. The loss dropped Toronto's record to 16-36. "It's unfortunate. It's a step back for us, and now we have to take three or four steps forward,'' Carter said. Carter said Detroit's defense was just too tough. "Their defensive schemes are just tremendous. They make you work for every basket. There are no easy baskets,'' Carter said. Peterson's three-point play and layup gave Toronto a 50-47 lead in third quarter, but the Pistons followed with a 18-5 run as Billups had seven points. The Pistons' reserves outscored Toronto's 30-6 as Detroit led 45-41 at halftime. Carter had eight points as the Raptors took a 23-12 lead in the first quarter. Atkins and Barry each had seven points as the Pistons responded with a 22-4 run to take a 34-27 lead with 5:54 left in the second quarter.

Game notes
Detroit has won three straight. ... Peterson had 20 points. ... Toronto outrebounded Detroit 48-38. Jerome Williams had 17 rebounds. ... Figure skaters Jamie Sale and David Pelletier sat courtside.
